        <h1>Why I Started GonoPBX</h1>
      </div>

      <div class="blog-article-content">

        <p>
          I work at a provider. Every day I see customers struggle with their phone systems.
          Not because the technology is inherently complex – but because the software they have to
          use makes it unnecessarily hard.
        </p>

        <h2>The problem</h2>

        <p>
          Most PBX interfaces look like they’re stuck 15 years in the past: endless menus,
          cryptic terminology, and settings that no normal person ever needs – yet they’re front and center.
          To create a single extension, you click through five different screens. To assign a number, you
          practically need an IT degree.
        </p>

        <p>
          The result: people call support. Not because something is broken, but because they don’t
          understand what they’re supposed to configure. That isn’t their fault – it’s the software’s fault.
        </p>

        <h2>The idea</h2>

        <p>
          At some point I asked myself: why isn’t there a phone system UI that is simply
          <strong>understandable</strong>? A UI you open and instantly know what to do.
          No manual, no training.
        </p>

        <p>
          I wanted to build something my mother could use. Or my neighbor. Or a small business that just
          wants to make calls without dealing with SIP headers and dialplan syntax.
        </p>

        <h2>The approach</h2>

        <p>
          GonoPBX hides the complexity. Under the hood runs Asterisk – a powerful, proven open-source PBX.
          But the interface only shows what you actually need:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>Create an extension – name, number, password, done</li>
          <li>Assign a number – pick DID, pick extension, done</li>
          <li>Call forwarding – one toggle, one destination, done</li>
          <li>Voicemail – enable, set PIN, enter email, done</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          No nested menus, no jargon where it doesn’t belong, no unnecessary options. And when you do need
          something technical – like codec selection or IP whitelisting – it’s in a separate admin area.
        </p>

        <h2>A side project</h2>

        <p>
          GonoPBX is not a startup and not a commercial product. It’s a hobby project that I develop in my
          free time. It grows release by release. Sometimes three features land in a week, sometimes nothing
          happens for weeks.
        </p>

        <p>
          And that’s the point. No pressure, no schedule – just the joy of building something I’d like to use
          myself. If it helps others too, even better.
        </p>

